{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/417640.A_Bright_Shining_Lie", "title": "A Bright Shining Lie: John Paul Vann and America in Vietnam", "titleComplete": "A Bright Shining Lie: John Paul Vann and America in Vietnam", "description": "This passionate, epic account of the Vietnam War centres on Lt Col John Paul Vann, whose story illuminates America's failures &amp; disillusionment in SE Asia. A field adviser to the army when US involvement was just beginning, he quickly became appalled at the corruption of the S. Vietnamese regime, their incompetence in fighting the Communists &amp; their brutal alienation of their own people. Finding his superiors too blinded by political lies to understand the war was being thrown away, he secretly briefed reporters on what was really happening. One of those reporters was Neil Sheehan.--Amazon (edited) Neil Sheehan was a Vietnam War correspondent for United Press International &amp; the NY Times &amp; won a number of awards for reporting. In 1971 he obtained the Pentagon Papers, which brought the Times the Pulitzer gold medal for meritorious public service. A Bright Shining Lie won the National Book Award &amp; the Pulitzer Prize for Non-Fiction. He lives in Washington DC.MapsThe funeral Going to war Antecedents to a confrontation The Battle of Ap Bac Taking on the system Antecedents to the man A second time aroundJohn Vann staysAcknowledgmentsInterviewsDocumentsSource NotesBibliographyIndexAbout the Author", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1350053421i/417640.jpg", "genres": ["American History", "Politics", "Asia", "Nonfiction", "American", "Military Fiction", "History", "Military History", "Biography", "War"], "asin": "0679724141", "isbn": "0679724141", "isbn13": "9780679724148", "publisher": "Vintage", "author": ["Neil Sheehan"], "publishDate": 622191600000, "ratingHistogram": [205, 371, 1672, 3937, 5858], "ratingsCount": 12043, "reviewsCount": 479, "numPages": 896, "language": "English", "awards": [{"name": "Pulitzer Prize", "awardedAt": 599644800000, "category": "General Nonfiction", "hasWon": null}, {"name": "National Book Award", "awardedAt": 568022400000, "category": "Nonfiction", "hasWon": null}, {"name": "Ambassador Book Award", "awardedAt": 599644800000, "category": "American Studies", "hasWon": null}, {"name": "National Book Critics Circle Award", "awardedAt": 568022400000, "category": "General Nonfiction", "hasWon": null}]}
{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/234633.Stilwell_and_the_American_Experience_in_China_1911_45", "title": "Stilwell and the American Experience in China, 1911-45", "titleComplete": "Stilwell and the American Experience in China, 1911-45", "description": "Barbara W. Tuchman won the Pulitzer Prize for Stilwell and the American Experience in China, 1911-45 in 1972. She uses the life of Joseph Stilwell, the military attache to China in 1935-39 and commander of United States forces and allied chief of staff to Chiang Kai-shek in 1942-44, to explore the history of China from the revolution of 1911 to the turmoil of World War II, when China's Nationalist government faced attack from Japanese invaders and Communist insurgents. Her story is an account of both American relations with China and the experiences of one of our men on the ground. In the cantankerous but level-headed \"Vinegar Joe,\" Tuchman found a subject who allowed her to perform, in the words of The National Review, \"one of the historian's most envied magic conjoining a fine biography of a man with a fascinating epic story.\"", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1388705286i/234633.jpg", "genres": ["American History", "China", "Asia", "Nonfiction", "Military Fiction", "History", "Military History", "Biography", "War", "World War II"], "asin": "0802138527", "isbn": "0802138527", "isbn13": "9780802138521", "publisher": "Grove Press", "author": ["John King Fairbank", "Barbara W. Tuchman"], "publishDate": 1002438000000, "characters": ["Joseph Stilwell"], "ratingHistogram": [55, 135, 559, 1250, 1525], "ratingsCount": 3524, "reviewsCount": 220, "numPages": 624, "language": "English", "awards": [{"name": "Pulitzer Prize", "awardedAt": 63100800000, "category": "General Nonfiction", "hasWon": null}, {"name": "National Book Award Finalist", "awardedAt": 63100800000, "category": "Biography", "hasWon": null}]}
{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/18728.No_Ordinary_Time", "title": "No Ordinary Time: Franklin and Eleanor Roosevelt: The Home Front in World War II", "titleComplete": "No Ordinary Time: Franklin and Eleanor Roosevelt: The Home Front in World War II", "description": "Winner of the Pulitzer for History, No Ordinary Time is a chronicle of one of the most vibrant &amp; revolutionary periods in US history. With an extraordinary collection of details, Goodwin weaves together a number of story lines\u2014the Roosevelt\u2019s marriage &amp; partnership, Eleanor\u2019s life as First Lady, &amp; FDR\u2019s White House &amp; its impact on America as well as on a world at war. Goodwin melds these into an intimate portrait of Eleanor &amp; Franklin Roosevelt &amp; of the time during which a new, modern America was born.", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1559635256i/18728.jpg", "genres": ["American History", "Politics", "Presidents", "Nonfiction", "History", "Biography Memoir", "Biography", "War", "World War II", "Historical"], "asin": "0684804484", "isbn": "0684804484", "isbn13": "9780684804484", "publisher": "Simon & Schuster", "author": ["Doris Kearns Goodwin"], "publishDate": 812530800000, "characters": ["Eleanor Roosevelt", "Franklin Delano Roosevelt"], "ratingHistogram": [1388, 1933, 5924, 13138, 22765], "ratingsCount": 45148, "reviewsCount": 1721, "numPages": 633, "language": "English", "awards": [{"name": "Pulitzer Prize", "awardedAt": 788947200000, "category": "History", "hasWon": null}, {"name": "Ambassador Book Award", "awardedAt": 788947200000, "category": "Biography", "hasWon": null}]}
{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/13425592-devil-in-the-grove", "title": "Devil in the Grove: Thurgood Marshall, the Groveland Boys, and the Dawn of a New America", "titleComplete": "Devil in the Grove: Thurgood Marshall, the Groveland Boys, and the Dawn of a New America", "description": "Devil in the Grove\u00a0is the winner of the 2013 Pulitzer Prize for General Nonfiction.Arguably the most important American lawyer of the twentieth century, Thurgood Marshall was on the verge of bringing the landmark suit Brown v. Board of Education before the U.S. Supreme Court when he became embroiled in an explosive and deadly case that threatened to change the course of the civil rights movement and cost him his life.In 1949, Florida\u2019s orange industry was booming, and citrus barons got rich on the backs of cheap Jim Crow labor. To maintain order and profits, they turned to Willis V. McCall, a violent sheriff who ruled Lake County with murderous resolve. When a white seventeen-year-old Groveland girl cried rape, McCall was fast on the trail of four young blacks who dared to envision a future for themselves beyond the citrus groves. By day\u2019s end, the Ku Klux Klan had rolled into town, burning the homes of blacks to the ground and chasing hundreds into the swamps, hell-bent on lynching the young men who came to be known as \u201cthe Groveland Boys.\u201dAnd so began the chain of events that would bring Thurgood Marshall, the man known as \u201cMr. Civil Rights,\u201d into the deadly fray. Associates thought it was suicidal for him to wade into the \u201cFlorida Terror\u201d at a time when he was irreplaceable to the burgeoning civil rights movement, but the lawyer would not shrink from the fight\u2014not after the Klan had murdered one of Marshall\u2019s NAACP associates involved with the case and Marshall had endured continual threats that he would be next.Drawing on a wealth of never-before-published material, including the FBI\u2019s unredacted Groveland case files, as well as unprecedented access to the NAACP\u2019s Legal Defense Fund files, King shines new light on this remarkable civil rights crusader, setting his rich and driving narrative against the heroic backdrop of a case that U.S. Supreme Court justice Robert Jackson decried as \u201cone of the best examples of one of the worst menaces to American justice.\u201d", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1366558408i/13425592.jpg", "genres": ["American History", "Law", "Politics", "Nonfiction", "Crime", "History", "True Crime", "Audiobook", "Biography", "Race"], "asin": "0062097717", "isbn": "0062097717", "isbn13": "9780062097712", "publisher": "Harper", "author": ["Gilbert King"], "publishDate": 1331020800000, "characters": ["Thurgood Marshall"], "places": ["Lake County, Florida", "Florida"], "ratingHistogram": [113, 285, 1294, 4886, 8111], "ratingsCount": 14689, "reviewsCount": 1904, "numPages": 434, "language": "English", "awards": [{"name": "Pulitzer Prize", "awardedAt": 1357027200000, "category": "General Nonfiction", "hasWon": null}, {"name": "Audie Award", "awardedAt": 1388563200000, "category": "History", "hasWon": null}, {"name": "Edgar Award", "awardedAt": 1357027200000, "category": "Best Fact Crime", "hasWon": null}, {"name": "Dayton Literary Peace Prize", "awardedAt": 1357027200000, "category": "Nonfiction", "hasWon": null}, {"name": "Florida Book Award", "awardedAt": 1325404800000, "category": "Non Fiction - Gold", "hasWon": null}, {"name": "Chautauqua Prize", "awardedAt": 1357027200000, "category": "", "hasWon": null}]}
{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/1424076.The_Good_War", "title": "The Good War: Oral History of WWII", "titleComplete": "The Good War: Oral History of WWII", "description": "Oral history evokes the innocent idealism, as well as the terror and horror, of ordinary Americans at home and abroad during World War II", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1266798888i/1424076.jpg", "genres": ["American History", "Nonfiction", "Military Fiction", "History", "Military History", "Biography", "Oral History", "War", "World War II", "Historical"], "asin": "B00295MBT2", "isbn": "0345325680", "isbn13": "9780345325686", "publisher": "Ballantine Books", "author": ["Studs Terkel"], "publishDate": 662716800000, "ratingHistogram": [45, 107, 595, 1515, 2274], "ratingsCount": 4536, "reviewsCount": 293, "numPages": 591, "language": "English", "awards": [{"name": "Pulitzer Prize", "awardedAt": 473414400000, "category": "General Nonfiction", "hasWon": null}]}
